Monte Carlo Simulation of the Three-dimensional Ising Spin Glass
Matteo Palassini1 and Sergio Caracciolo2
1 Department of Physics, University of California, Santa Cruz, California 95064 2 Scuola Normale Superiore and INFN, 56100 Pisa, Italy
Abstract. We study the 3D Edwards–Anderson model with binary interactions by Monte Carlo simulations. Direct evidence of finite–size scaling is provided, and the universal finite–size scaling functions are determined. Using an iterative extrapolation procedure, Monte Carlo data are extrapolated to infinite volume up to correlation length ξ ≈ 140. The infinite volume data are consistent with both a continuous phase transition at finite temperature and an essential singularity at finite temperature. An essential singularity at zero temperature is excluded.
1 Introduction
Understanding the thermodynamics of spin glasses represents a challenging unsolved problem for statistical and computational physics [1]. The very existence of a phase transition in the 3D Ising spin glass is still unclear. Previous Monte Carlo (MC) simulations [2,3,4,5,6] give a certain evidence of a Tc 6= 0 continuous transition with power-law divergence of ξ at T → T +
c . However,
they cannot exclude completely neither an exponential divergence at T → 0+ [2,3,4], nor a line of critical points at T ≤ Tc 6= 0 [4,6,7], which implies an exponential divergence at T → Tc+. Furthermore, the important topic of finite-size scaling (FSS) has not been much investigated for spin glasses. Here, we study the 3D Ising spin glass by MC simulations of moderatesize systems in the paramagnetic phase (less hampered by long equilibration times), using the powerful FSS method of [8]. In Sect. 2 details on the simulations are given. In Sect. 3 a direct evidence of FSS, independent of the nature of the divergence of ξ, is provided, and the universal FSS functions are determined for the first time [9]. The MC data are extrapolated to infinite volume up to ξ one order of magnitude larger than before. In Sect. 4 the critical behavior of the extrapolated data is analyzed.
