4 Nature of the phase transition
We now compare our extrapolated data with the three different scenarios compatible with previous simulations.
(i) Power–law singularity at Tc 6= 0. We fit our data to
ξ(T ) = cξ (T − Tc)−ν [1 + aξ (T − Tc)θ] (6)
χSG(ξ) = b ξ2−η [1 + d ξ−∆] (7)
with fixed θ and ∆. Without corrections to scaling (aξ = d = 0), the fit parameters show small systematic variations when we vary the fit interval. The fits stabilize with 1 ≤ θ ≤ 2 and 1 ≤ ∆ ≤ 1.5, the preferred values being θ = 1.4 and ∆ = 1.3 (goodness of fit parameter Q > 0.6 and Q > 0.98 resp.). Our estimates for the critical parameters are Tc = 1.156±0.015, ν = 1.8±0.2, and η = −0.26±0.04. Corrections to scaling are important for ξ ≤ 10 (Fig.3). (ii) Essential singularity at Tc 6= 0. Our data fit very well also to
ξ(T ) = fξ exp(gξ/(T − Tc)σ) . (8)
For ξ ≥ 3.8 the best fit (shown in Fig.3b) gives σ = 0.5 ± 0.3, Tc = 1.08 ± 0.04 (Q = 0.69). Deviations from this fit for ξ < 3 are consistent with corrections to scaling of ≈ 10%. Since for an exponential singularity we expect multiplicative logarithmic corrections, we tried also the fit
χSG(ξ) = bl ξ2−ηl (log ξ)r (9)
obtaining ηl = −0.36 ± 0.03 and r = −0.36 ± 0.06 (Q > 0.9) (see Fig.3a). (iii) Essential singularity at T = 0. Fitting our data to
ξ(T ) = fξ exp(gξ/T σ) (10)


